<item>
            <title>[SPARK-45415] RocksDB consumes excessive disk space when many concurrent streaming queries are using dedup</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SPARK-45415</link>
                <project id="12315420" key="SPARK">Spark</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;Our spark environment features a number of parallel structured streaming jobs, many of which use state store. Most use state store for dropDuplicates and work with a tiny amount of information, but a few have a substantially large state store requiring use of RocksDB. In such a configuration, spark allocates a minimum of &lt;tt&gt;spark.sql.shuffle.partitions * queryCount&lt;/tt&gt;&#160;partitions, each of which pre-allocate about 74mb (observed on EMR/Hadoop) disk storage for RocksDB. This allocation is due to pre-allocation of log files space using&#160;&lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/facebook/rocksdb/blob/main/include/rocksdb/options.h#L871-L880&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;fallocate&lt;/a&gt;, requiring users to either unnaturally reduce shuffle partitions, split running spark instances, or allocate a large amount of wasted storage.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
                <environment>&lt;p&gt;Apache spark on AWS EMR, local spark on a laptop on Linux.&#160; Does not impact MacOS due to missing support in RocksDB for pre-allocation (MacOS does not support the fallocate system call).&lt;/p&gt;</environment>
